{"title_page": "Philip Gawdy", "text_new": "'''Philip Gawdy''' (1562-1617) was an English landowner and letter writer.\n\nPhilip Gawdy was the son of [[Bassingbourne Gawdy (died 1590)|Bassingbourne Gawdy, senior]], and Anne Wotton (d. 1586). In 1588 his father married Margaret Syliard, widow of Thomas Darcy of Tolleshunt Darcy.<ref>Jeayes (1906), pp. viii-ix.</ref>\n\nHe was the younger brother of [[Bassingbourne Gawdy (died 1606)|Bassingbourne Gawdy, junior]], who married Anne Framlingham, of Crows Hall, [[Debenham]], in 1586.<ref>Jeayes (1906), p. x.</ref>\n\nAt first Philip Gawdy studied law in London, and looked for opportunities at the royal court. In 1591 he joined the crew of the ''[[English ship Revenge (1577)|Revenge]]'' commanded by Sir [[Richard Grenville]] in a small fleet under [[Thomas Howard, 1st Earl of Suffolk|Lord Thomas Howard]]. After encountering the Spanish at the [[Battle of Flores (1591)]], Gawdy was captured and imprisoned in Lisbon at [[S\u00e3o Jorge Castle]]. He was released after undertaking to pay \u00a3200 in an exchange of prisoners.<ref>Jeayes (1906), pp. xi-xiv.</ref>\n\nPhilip then mostly lived at [[Harling, Norfolk|West Harling]].\n\nIn 1605 his nephew, Bassingbourne junior's son, [[Framlingham Gawdy]], had an unsuitable affair with a Miss Havers of Harling, and Philip Gawdy took him to London, showing him the lions at the [[Tower of London]], the royal tombs at [[Westminster Abbey]], and the court, where his \"cousins\" [[Mary Gargrave]] and [[Elizabeth Howard, Countess of Carrick|Elizabeth Southwell (1584-1631)]], the latter from nearby [[Woodrising, Norfolk]], were maids of honour to [[Anne of Denmark]].<ref>Jeays (1906), pp. xvi, 150, 160.</ref>\n\nGawdy married Bridget (d. 1609), daughter of Bartholomew Strangman of Hadleigh, Essex.\n\nGawdy's letters are held by the [[British Library]].\n\n==References==\n* [https://archive.org/details/cu31924027985260/page/n6/mode/2up Isaac Herbert Jeayes, ''Letters of Philip Gawdy of West Harling, Norfolk, and of London to various members of his family, 1579-1616'' (London, 1906).]\n* Walter Rye, ''HMC 10th Report, Appendix II'', (London, 1889).\n* [http://www.histparl.ac.uk/volume/1604-1629/member/gawdy-philip-1562-1617 'GAWDY, Philip (1562-1617), of West Harling, Norfolk and Whitehall; later of Chancery Lane, London', ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1604-1629'', ed. Andrew Thrush and John P. Ferris, 2010.]\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gawdy, Philip}}\n[[Category:1562 births]]\n[[Category:1617 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Harling, Norfolk]]\n", "text_old": "'''Philip Gawdy''' (1562-1617) was an English landowner and letter writer.\n\nPhilip Gawdy was the son of [[Bassingbourne Gawdy (died 1590)|Bassingbourne Gawdy, senior]], and Anne Wotton (d. 1586). In 1588 his father married Margaret Syliard, widow of Thomas Darcy of Tolleshunt Darcy.<ref>Jeayes (1906), pp. viii-ix.</ref>\n\nHe was the younger brother of [[Bassingbourne Gawdy (died 1606)|Bassingbourne Gawdy, junior]], who married Anne Framlingham, of Crows Hall, [[Debenham]], in 1586.<ref>Jeayes (1906), p. x.</ref>\n\nAt first Philip Gawdy studied law in London, and looked for opportunities at the royal court. In 1591 he joined the crew of the ''[[English ship Revenge (1577)|Revenge]]'' commanded by Sir [[Richard Grenville]] in a small fleet under [[Thomas Howard, 1st Earl of Suffolk|Lord Thomas Howard]]. After encountering the Spanish at the [[Battle of Flores (1591)]], Gawdy was captured and imprisoned in Lisbon at [[S\u00e3o Jorge Castle]]. He was released after undertaking to pay \u00a3200 in an exchange of prisoners.<ref>Jeayes (1906), pp. xi-xiv.</ref>\n\nPhilip then mostly lived at [[Harling, Norfolk|West Harling]].\n\nIn 1605 his nephew, Bassingbourne junior's son, [[Framlingham Gawdy]], had an unsuitable affair with a Miss Havers of Harling, and Philip Gawdy took him to London, showing him the lions at the [[Tower of London]], the royal tombs at [[Westminster Abbey]], and the court, where his \"cousins\" [[Mary Gargrave]] and [[Elizabeth Howard, Countess of Carrick|Elizabeth Southwell (1584-1631)]], the latter from nearby [[Woodrising, Norfolk]], were maids of honour to [[Anne of Denmark]].<ref>Jeays (1906), pp. xvi, 150, 160.</ref>\n\nHis letters mention shopping in London, including \n\nGawdy married Bridget (d. 1609), daughter of Bartholomew Strangman of Hadleigh, Essex.\n\nGawdy's letters are held by the [[British Library]].\n\n==References==\n* [https://archive.org/details/cu31924027985260/page/n6/mode/2up Isaac Herbert Jeayes, ''Letters of Philip Gawdy of West Harling, Norfolk, and of London to various members of his family, 1579-1616'' (London, 1906).]\n* Walter Rye, ''HMC 10th Report, Appendix II'', (London, 1889).\n* [http://www.histparl.ac.uk/volume/1604-1629/member/gawdy-philip-1562-1617 'GAWDY, Philip (1562-1617), of West Harling, Norfolk and Whitehall; later of Chancery Lane, London', ''The History of Parliament: the House of Commons 1604-1629'', ed. Andrew Thrush and John P. Ferris, 2010.]\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gawdy, Philip}}\n[[Category:1562 births]]\n[[Category:1617 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Harling, Norfolk]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_Gawdy"}
